			<ns0:name>dsch...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/104270846665912603141/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">On all OSes, the x86 floating point control word (which controls, in particular, rounding and precision), is clobbered by nacl syscalls. Instead it should be preserved.

It matters a lot more in x86-32 where SSE is less likely to be used.

Attached is a simple reproducing test.

I'm guessing this should be M15 because it breaks Mono (on x86-32).</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-10-18T17:19:50.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-10-14T22:04:24.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
